us and restricted workers’ consumption in support of industrial growth. Focusing on the daily operations of planning in the ethnically mixed city of Cluj from 1945 to 1955, this book argues that socialist accumulation was deeply contradictory: it not only inherited some of the classical tensions of capital accumulation, but also generated its own, which derived from the multivocal nature of the state socialist worker as a creator of value, as living labour, and as a subject of emancipatory politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCentral planningzRomaniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGovernment ownershipzRomaniazCluj-NapocaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocialismzRomaniazCluj-NapocaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzRomaniazCluj-NapocaxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aRomania, Socialist Transformation, Socialist Industrialization, Socialist Accumulation, Cluj.1 aKalb, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311099772940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789201864?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789201864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781789201864/original  a978-3-11-099772-9  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK